The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | DAY I HIGHLIGHTS 
                                                                                                                       7                                      DAY I HIGHLIGHTS 
                      
	 India finally won the toss after losing in 10 consecutive matches. These 10 tosses were lost between 2nd December 2009 to 9th October 2010. However the last time India batted first in a Test was eight Tests ago against Bangladesh on 17th January 2010. Bangladesh on that occasion had won the toss and put India into bat.         
	 When the pair of Virender Sehwag and Gautam Gambhir added 45 runs, they became the most successful opening pair for India in Tests in terms of aggregate runs. The duo now has 3026 runs in 55 innings. Sunil Gavaskar and Chetan Chauhan are second with 3010 runs in 59 innings.         
	 On 52, Sehwag bettered his previous highest score in Ahmedabad. He had scored 51 on his previous outing at this venue vs SL last November.         
	 On 96, Sehwag became the second batsman to score 1000 runs in 2010. The other being Tendulkar (1283 runs). Sehwag now has 1077 runs this year.         
	 Sehwag registered his 22nd Test century, 21st in the 1st innings, 18th at No. 2, 12th at home, 5th in 2010, 2nd vs NZ and first on this ground.         
	 Virender Sehwag (82 Tests, 140 inngs) now has the most runs scored after 140 Test innings. Sehwag, now with 7325 runs, went past Walter Hammond who had 7249 runs after 140 innings. Tendulkar had 7200.         
	 On 205 the Sehwag-Dravid partnership set a new record for the second wicket for India in Tests vs New Zealand. The previous best was 204 by Gavaskar amp; Surinder Amarnath in Auckland in 1976.         
	 Sehwag (173) also bettered his previous highest score vs New Zealand in Tests. His previous highest was 130 in Mohali, October 2003.         
	 This was the 14th time Sehwag has made a score exceeding 150. Sachin (20) leads the list with 150-plus scores followed by Brian Lara 19 and Donald Bradman (18).         
	 Dravid recorded his 30th Test hundred, 25th in the 1st innings, 24 at No. 3, 13th at home, 5th vs New Zealand and second in 2010.         
	 Incidentally, Dravids hundred was also the 400th century scored by an Indian in Test cricket. England with 766 centuries tops the list followed by Australia 736, West Indies (432) and India (400).           COMPILED BY MOHANDAS MENON                                                                                                                 
